      <title>About Us</title>
      <link href="/2022/10/08/About-me/"/>
      <url>/2022/10/08/About-me/</url>
      
        <content type="html"><![CDATA[<h3 id="About-Me"><a href="#About-Me" class="headerlink" title="About Me"></a>About Me</h3><ul><li>Dr. Fei LIU (刘非) received his Ph.D. in 2020. He is now working as a faculty member at Chongqing Jiaotong University (重庆交通大学) (2020-).  </li><li>Dr. Liu’s research interests include developing novel methods in urban flood and coastal inundation management as well as the applications. Both aspects of scientific and technological research are considered.  </li><li>Undergraduate Courses: Simulation Technology for Urban Stormwater (城市雨洪模拟技术), Urban Flood Defence and Stormwater Management (城镇防洪与雨水管理), Building Fire Engineering (建筑消防工程)</li><li>Postgraduate Courses: Process and analysis of scientific data (科学数据处理与分析)</li></ul><h3 id="To-prospective-students"><a href="#To-prospective-students" class="headerlink" title="To prospective students:"></a>To prospective students:</h3><ul><li>Due to the rapid urbanization and climate change, heavy rainfall is likely to happen in a more frequent and intensive manner. To better understand the characteristics and mechanism of urban flood in this context, numerical models can be applied. Basically, in my team, one-dimensional drainage pipe model like SWMM, and two-dimensional flood model such as FVCOM and Lisflood are used. To know more, you can access the links in the bottom.</li><li>The inundation induced by storm surge, tsunami and river flood in coastal areas (e.g., Tokyo Bay) is also studied using numerical models like FVCOM.</li><li>Now five postgraduate students are studying under my guidance. I also collaborate with other professors of our department in supervising students. If you are interested in the topics, welcome to join us.</li><li>Please feel free to contact me: <a href="mailto:&#102;&#x65;&#105;&#46;&#108;&#105;&#x75;&#x40;&#99;&#x71;&#106;&#x74;&#117;&#46;&#x65;&#100;&#117;&#x2e;&#x63;&#x6e;">&#102;&#x65;&#105;&#46;&#108;&#105;&#x75;&#x40;&#99;&#x71;&#106;&#x74;&#117;&#46;&#x65;&#100;&#117;&#x2e;&#x63;&#x6e;</a></li></ul><hr><p><a href="https://www.epa.gov/water-research/storm-water-management-model-swmm">SWMM</a><br><a href="http://fvcom.smast.umassd.edu/">FVCOM</a><br><a href="https://www.bristol.ac.uk/geography/research/hydrology/models/lisflood/downloads/">Lisflood</a></p>]]></content>
      
      
